Excellent service and phenomenal food! Located near the Capitol Hilton, on 15th St NW, Claudia's classy elegance is a  great find. We began with cocktails and mussels. The bartender made a perfect old fashion and a solid regular mojito, not the one made like an icee.  The mussels were soaked in a white wine jalapeno sauce. To add to this deliciousness, fries were poured on the bottom to give us something to collect that awesome juice with.....a straw might also have worked. For our entree, we ordered the Lobster Paella for 2. This was a beautiful plate of food! This dish was overwhelming and wonderful to look at. A 2.5 pound lobster sat quite majestically in the middle of the pan on top of a gorgeous mound of saffron infused rice. Imbedded in the rice like little treasures we found shrimp and calamari, all surrounded by more mussels than I could count...or eat. We did not need that appetizer and there was plenty left over. Did I mention the wine list that was decent but had few by the glass options. They want you to buy the bottle. We chose the Oakwood Merlot, which was very tasty. There was also live music, flamenco dancers. The music was awesome but the dancers a tad underwhelming in comparison. I am used to a more vibrant flamenco than these ladies presented. This is now a go to restaurant when I am in DC. For the area it is very decently priced. The two of us had drinks and dinner for $150 plus tip. We had a District Discount Card, given to us at the Hilton as Hilton Honors members, which gave us 15% off our bill. Parking is always an issue in this part of DC, well all of DC, so plan to pay. Claudia's is well worth the your time should you find yourself in D.C.

The crab cake was to die for.  There wasn't a lot of breading used for a filler in the crab cake.  They use corn,  peppers and other things which was different and great. If I could give Claudia's a ZERO I would for customer service, responsiveness and tact!   We held a company event there in December 2018 and the event coordinator Aron Schultz was horrible to deal with.  It took him weeks to respond to my requests, but the "real magic" happened on the day of out holiday event,. 1.  They were late with the set-up.  When we walked in, it was like they were not having our event. HE apologized and claimed to be sick the previous day.   Staff sat outside of the room with a dazed and confused look as they scrambled to set things up.  2. Serving utensils were missing, we paid for a full bar, alcohol came out late. 3.  I had to ask then to start bringing the food to the group.  Drama! While the staff recovered well enough, it was Aron's bad attitude about the entire ordeal that sucked.  After the event, I reached out to him to see what the restaurant would be willing to do on our invoice to compensate for the service issues.  He said that they are not responsible for issuing credits for every customer who is dissatisfied with the level of service they provide.  isn't that what real reputable businesses do, correct their mistakes?  They were wiling to give a small credit to compensate for their service mayhem, but to add insult to injury,  that tactless General Manager Marlon Alfaro said that no further discount or credits would be applied to our account. I would be surprised if this place is in business this spring.   What a horrible experience!  I will be telling EVERYONE in my social circle and  professional network NEVER to use them for anything!   Thumbs DOWN to this place!

Full disclosure, I’m a big fan. The drinks are strong and the food is on point. The bartenders are an absolute trip that’ll make sure your drinks are made 2 perfection. Truth is, Claudia’s is considered a hidden jem to those that bust their chops on the K street corridor. I’m very grateful that I can let loose and get served quality within a short period of time. All without breaking the bank. That’s probably why the local K street event managers in the know, religiously make Claudia’s the indefinite go to bar for Xmas, New Years, & weekly to monthly morale parties. I find that most of the time the bar is relatively busy. However, when it isn’t the bartenders are always very attentive and gracious. I guess that with all the nightclubs in the area Claudia’s is a great special occasion & pregame spot.

There’s also a happy hour bar menu which is way way above par. I would describe the food as steakhouse oriented with a Spanish influence. The bar almost needs their own review as the bartenders are a totally eclectic group of pro’s. They churn out killer drinks as if they could do it in their sleep. And when they’re not bogged down with cocktail orders each and everyone is an absolute pleasure to talk to. Thank you, Matt & Chuck we’ll be seeing you soon. Cheers!!

I celebrated my birthday at Claudia's last week. I was attracted to Claudia's because of the chic decor and upscale menu selections.  I was not disappointed in these areas. But my dining experience at Claudia's last week, left me and my guests feeling a tad disrespected by our server because we were ignored for most of the evening (before and after our food came out). We sat unattended with empty water glasses at many points throughout the evening. I rounded up my closest family and friends for a special night out in town -my birthday celebration, and had a limo driver waiting on us outside (we exceeded our limo rental time by waiting around for our server). Our server did not do the minimal gesture of wishing me a happy birthday.  There was zero engagement. We paid the $25 cake cutting fee which was reasonable because we brought in an outside two tier cake. After handing the cake over to the server to take in the kitchen to cut and bring back out to serve, one of my sisters had to follow up to see if she was planning to bring the cake back out anytime soon? We spent a chunk of money on our tab, and expected at least good, if not exceptional service.  In sum, the food was great. Service not so great.

Claudia's steakhouse has a cool happy hour with a variety of food choice although limited in beer choices. Make sure you are ready for the kick that come with the wings. Review update: I went back for a special event in the private room and it was amazing. Food was delicious and the party all night was night was fun with great drinks. Follow on Istagram: @fallyns_foodie_excursions #claudiassteakhousedc #fallynsfoodieexcursions

Food here was surprisingly very good. The fried plantain chips were crunchy and similar to a thick kettle chip crispy. The salad was mostly iceberg lettuce but the sauce and accompanying ingredients made a refreshing dish. The salmon, a fish very easily overcooked, was delightfully tender without being raw. The side of asparagus could be charred a little less. Mashed potatoes have a hidden spiciness to them! The beer soaked brown sugar drunken ribeye steak was pretty good overall, however they didn't ask how we wanted it cooked. When asked, they said they cook a tender pink medium steak but did not take a request to make it medium rare. Strangely while most of the steak was a tender medium consistency, a smaller side portion was closer to a better medium rare to rare consistency. The cheesecake was pretty good overall. The warm chocolate cake was a bit dry on the sides but delicately smooth like pudding. The desserts had a contrasting tart sauce that overpowered the cheesecake just a little bit.
What an incredible meal. The service was incredible too.

Claudia's is a nice, new addition to the DC restaurant scene, just a year old. The portions were a good size, but the price did rack up fairly quickly, lol. Staff was fantastic and we enjoyed the complementary plantain crisps and amuse-bouche of the chef's soup selection was nice way to set expectations.  Pros:  side dishes were large and plentiful for sharing, we got the honey-fried Brussel sprouts (good, but not fabulous) and French fries (seasoned and done the way I like); the rack of lamb was a set of two thick portions (6 ribs) and was well prepared (I was happy that med-rare was pretty rare); the drunken steak was alright, but my friend ordered it med-well, so it was too done for me; the petite filet mignon was nice, but I've tasted better; booth was nice and comfortably fix 5 adults and made it easy to face each other and share plates. Cons:  there is live flamenco music and dancers, which was entertaining, but MUCH too LOUD for conversation with a group.  Over all, I would say it may be pricy, but fine for a date night where you can sit close to the person you want to talk with or just not talk at all. LoL I probably won't go back for dinner, but I would stop in for their happy hour at the bar and try that - looked like it was most of their Small Plates priced ~$3 cheaper and tempting cocktails in the $5 to $7 range.
